thread.title: Kevin Harvick wins at Dover; Jimmie Johnson eliminated from Chase
thread.title_full: Kevin Harvick wins at Dover; Jimmie Johnson eliminated from Chase

author: azcentral.com
title: Kevin Harvick wins at Dover; Jimmie Johnson eliminated from Chase
text:
DOVER, Del. — A look at all the results and action from Sunday’s Chase for the Sprint Cup race at Dover International Speedway:
WINNER: Kevin Harvick pulled off an incredible victory in a must-win scenario, dominating Dover to advance to the second round of the Chase and keep his back-to-back championship hopes alive. Harvick faced elimination if he didn’t win the race after a crash at Chicagoland and an empty fuel tank at New Hampshire, but he was untouchable all day at Dover and ran away with the victory. The win with his back against the wall was the third such instance for Harvick in two years.
"Obviously we weren't in a great position coming into today, but this is what it's all about — these big-time moments," Harvick said in victory lane. "I think we're better that we were last year just because of all the experiences we've had," the reigning Sprint Cup Series champion added.
USA TODAY
Kevin Harvick's NASCAR career
OUT OF THE CHASE: Dover was an elimination race for the first round of the Chase, which narrowed the field from 16 drivers to 12 with seven races to go. Clint Bowyer never mounted much of a threat and was unable to get himself out of the Chase basement, Paul Menard’s disappointing day kept him out of the top 12, and Jimmie Johnson suffered a shocking mechanical failure. Meanwhile, Jamie McMurray, who finished fourth Sunday, was knocked out in a tiebreaker with Dale Earnhardt Jr.
"We were driving so hard on those last few laps," McMurray said. "We haven't run this well, obviously, all year long. I'm thrilled with our performance today but frustrated we weren't able to make it to the next round."
USA TODAY
Dale Earnhardt Jr. barely advances in Chase for the Sprint Cup
STUNNING OUSTER: Johnson, the 10-time Dover winner and six-time NASCAR champion, was shockingly eliminated when he had something break in his drive line on lap 102. He went straight to the garage for repairs, but fell to 43rd place in the meantime. He returned to the race 36 laps behind the leaders with his Chase fate in the hands of other drivers.
"It's not the way we wanted to end the season," Johnson said. "With this format, a bad finish can take you out, end your chances. "You've got to be on for 10 races. This is definitely not what we wanted or hoped, but that's racing."
UNAPPROVED ADJUSTMENTS: Martin Truex Jr. was forced to start in the rear of the field after NASCAR ruled his team made an unapproved adjustment to the right rear after inspection. Truex had already gone through inspection when NASCAR suspected his team had done something to bow out the right side. Another trip through the laser grid confirmed NASCAR’s suspicion, which put Truex in the 43rd position. Officials determined no other penalty would be assessed.
WINDY DAY: The dire rain forecasts at Dover proved to be incorrect, but it wasn’t a nice day – particularly when it came to a strong wind. The wind blew plastic wrappers (like from hot dogs) all over the track, and several drivers had some stick to their grilles. Drivers like Ryan Newman, Kevin Harvick and Jeff Gordon had to use other cars to get rid of the debris.
